questionTemplates.text:
M: How about going fishing this Sunday?
W: That's a good idea.
{a}

W: I like skating but not skiing.
M: Well, skiing, bowling and golf are my favorite sports.
{a}

W: Professor Clark said that the mid-term exam would cover the first 15 lessons?
M: Really? I thought it only included the first 12 lessons. Then I must spendthe weekend to go over the rest of the lessons.
{a}

M: Let's go to Disneyland after supper, Sue.
W: That's a realty good idea, but I have to meet Mr Black at the airport.
{a}

F: I want a single morn.
M: It's 180 yuan a day.
{a}

W: Jack, would you like to go to the club with us tomorrow night?
M: I wish I could, but I have to work on my term paper.
{a}

M: I have passed the test.
W: Congratulations.
{a}

W: Sometimes when I'm busy, I let my baby watch videos. Can this help his mental development?
M: Passive activity probably won't hurt, but TV and videos are poor substitutes for parents' involvement.
{a}

M: I'm really surprised you got an A on the test; you didn't seem to have done a lot of reading.
W: Now you know why I never missed the lecture.
{a}

M: Can you come over for lunch on Saturday?
W: I'd love to, but I've got a dentist's appointment at eleven thirty.
{a}

M: When I sell my paintings, I'm going to buy a new car.
W: Well, don't count your chickens before they are hatched.
{a}

W: Excuse me, but could you tell me where I can change American Dollars into British Pounds?
M: There is a bank around the corner, but I'm afraid it's already past it's closing time. Why don't you try the one near the railway station?
{a}

W: Which would you like, coffee or tea?
M: Tea.
{a}

W: Tom, who won the basketball game yesterday?
M: We won by 50 to 36.
{a}

W: How's your new flat?
M: Oh, it's okay, thanks. We've been there a month now, and I think we're going to like it.
{a}

W: If you have time, will you mail a letter for me tomorrow?
M: I'd be glad to.
{a}

W: This is one of our best and least expensive two-bedroom listings. It's located in a quiet building and it's close to bus lines.
M: That may be true. But look at it, it's awful, the paint has peeled off and the carpet is worn and the stove is ancient.
{a}

M: How about my food? I've been sitting here for almost half an hour.
W: I'm sorry, sir. It must be ready by now.
{a}

M: Come on in. Make yourself at home.
W: Thanks. You have a nice house.
{a}

W: Do you like milk?
M: No, I don't. I don't like it at all.
{a}

M: May I have a look at that V-neck shirt?
W: Sure, which color do you prefer?
{a}

W: Why don't you turn on the light. It's so dark.
M: I don't know where the switch is. My glasses are gone.
{a}

F: Did you watch the football match yesterday?
M: Yes, I did. No. 5 Middle School beat us 4:2.
{a}

M: Would you get me through to Dr. Lemon please?
W: I'm sorry. He's with a patient.
{a}

W: Do you want me to explain these questions before the exam?
M: What's the point? I don't understand a single word in it! It seems as if they were written in a foreign language.
{a}
